phic name for someone who lived beside a stream, from southern Middle English <i>bourne</i>, Old English <i>burna</i>, <i>burne</i> ‘spring, stream’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example Bourn in Cambridgeshire or Bourne in Lincolnshire. In surnames the reference is often to an old stream called <i>burna</i>, surviving as the name of a farm. This word was replaced as the general word for a stream in southern dialects by Old English <i>brōc</i> (see   Brook  ) and came to be restricted in meaning to a stream flowing only intermittently, especially in winter."],"variants":[{"name":"Burn","meanings":["English (Northumberland and Durham): variant of   Bourne  ."]},{"name":"Bourn","meanings":["English (southeastern): variant of   Bourne  ."]},{"name":"Born","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Heinz, Helmut, Berthold, Frieda, Friedrich, Fritz, Gerhard, Horst, Jutta.","English: variant of   Bourne  .","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>borgne</i> ‘one-eyed, squint-eyed’."]},{"name":"Cockburn","meanings":["Scottish (Midlothian) and northern English: habitational name from a place in Berwickshire named Cockburn, from Old English <i>cocc</i> ‘cock, rooster’ (or the related byname <i>Cocca</i>) + <i>burna</i> ‘stream’ (see   Bourne  ). This surname is traditionally pronounced <i>Coburn</i>."]},{"name":"Bournes","meanings":["English: variant of   Bourne   with plural or post-medieval exrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Brook","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a brook, stream, water-meadows or low, marshy ground, from Middle English <i>brook</i>, Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, such as Brook (Kent, Rutland) or Brooke (Norfolk).","North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a water meadow or marsh, from Low German <i>brook</i> (cognate with German   Bruch   ‘swamp’ and Old English <i>brōc</i>; see 1 above).","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Broek</b>: topographic name from <i>broek</i>, a cognate of 2 above."]},{"name":"Burne","meanings":["English: variant of   Bourne  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705205,"age":5,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":7,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":21,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Bourne was born about 1564, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England. He had at least 5 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"abt 1564–":"umbes 1564–Surnud","1590–Male":"1590–Surnud","1593–1593":"1593–1593","1594–Male":"1594–Surnud","1598–Male":"1598–Surnud","1600–Male":"1600–Surnud","1600–1633":"1600–1633","1564–Male":"1564–Surnud","1569":"1569","1633":"1633","1600":"1600","1598":"1598","1564":"1564","1585":"1585","1594":"1594","1571":"1571","1593":"1593","1590":"1590","abt 1564":"umbes 1564","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"abt